optionsEn:
  - "$x=\\dfrac{\\pi}{12}+\\dfrac{k\\pi}{3}$ or $x=\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}+\\dfrac{k\\pi}{1}$ (including solutions from $\\sin(10x)+\\sin(-2x)=1$)"
  - "$x=\\dfrac{\\pi}{4}+k\\pi$"
  - "$x=k\\pi$"
  - "no solutions"
correct: 0
hints:
  - "① Zastosuj wzór na iloczyn na sumę: $2\\sin A\\cos B=\\sin(A+B)+\\sin(A-B)$. Tutaj $A=4x$, $B=6x$."
  - "② Lewa strona: $4\\sin(4x)\\cos(6x)=2[\\sin(10x)+\\sin(-2x)]=2\\sin(10x)-2\\sin(2x)$."
  - "③ Równanie: $2\\sin(10x)-2\\sin(2x)=2\\sin(10x)+1$, czyli $-2\\sin(2x)=1$, $\\sin(2x)=-\\tfrac{1}{2}$. Stąd $2x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}+2k\\pi$ lub $2x=\\pi+\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}+2k\\pi$, czyli $x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{12}+k\\pi$ lub $x=\\tfrac{7\\pi}{12}+k\\pi$."
hintsEn:
  - "① Apply the product-to-sum formula: $2\\sin A\\cos B=\\sin(A+B)+\\sin(A-B)$. Here $A=4x$, $B=6x$."
  - "② Left side: $4\\sin(4x)\\cos(6x)=2[\\sin(10x)+\\sin(-2x)]=2\\sin(10x)-2\\sin(2x)$."
  - "③ Equation: $2\\sin(10x)-2\\sin(2x)=2\\sin(10x)+1$, i.e. $-2\\sin(2x)=1$, $\\sin(2x)=-\\tfrac{1}{2}$. Hence $2x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}+2k\\pi$ or $2x=\\pi+\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}+2k\\pi$, i.e. $x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{12}+k\\pi$ or $x=\\tfrac{7\\pi}{12}+k\\pi$."
tests:
  trig_eq: 1.0
