  - "$x=\\tfrac{\\pi}{4}+k\\pi$"
  - "no solutions"
correct: 0
hints:
  - "① $3\\cos^2 x-3\\sin^2 x=3\\cos(2x)$, a $\\sqrt{3}\\sin(2x)$ zostaje. Zatem równanie: $3\\cos(2x)+\\sqrt{3}\\sin(2x)=0$."
  - "② Podziel przez $\\cos(2x)$ (sprawdź osobno $\\cos(2x)=0$): $3+\\sqrt{3}\\tan(2x)=0$, czyli $\\tan(2x)=-\\sqrt{3}$."
  - "③ $2x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}+k\\pi$, $x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}+\\tfrac{k\\pi}{2}$. Wybierz $k$ tak, by $x\\in[-\\pi,\\pi]$: $x\\in\\{-\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3},-\\tfrac{\\pi}{6},\\tfrac{\\pi}{3},\\tfrac{5\\pi}{6}\\}$."
hintsEn:
  - "① $3\\cos^2 x-3\\sin^2 x=3\\cos(2x)$, and $\\sqrt{3}\\sin(2x)$ remains. So the equation: $3\\cos(2x)+\\sqrt{3}\\sin(2x)=0$."
  - "② Divide by $\\cos(2x)$ (check $\\cos(2x)=0$ separately): $3+\\sqrt{3}\\tan(2x)=0$, i.e. $\\tan(2x)=-\\sqrt{3}$."
  - "③ $2x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{3}+k\\pi$, $x=-\\tfrac{\\pi}{6}+\\tfrac{k\\pi}{2}$. Choose $k$ so that $x\\in[-\\pi,\\pi]$: $x\\in\\{-\\tfrac{2\\pi}{3},-\\tfrac{\\pi}{6},\\tfrac{\\pi}{3},\\tfrac{5\\pi}{6}\\}$."
tests:
  trig_eq: 1.0
  trig_formulas: 0.7
